2. Founder persona
Act as a startup founder. How should I build a task management mobile app for students?

#OUTPUT :
As a founder who's been through this, let me give you the real playbook — not the textbook version.

🧠 First, Kill the "Just Build It" Urge
Every first-time founder wants to jump straight into building. Don't. The graveyard of apps is full of perfectly built products nobody wanted. Your first 2 weeks should produce zero code and zero UI — just ruthless validation.
Talk to 20 students. Ask:

"How do you track assignments and deadlines right now?"
"What's the most stressful part of managing your academic workload?"
"Show me what's on your phone for this."

You'll likely discover they're using a WhatsApp group, a crumpled notebook, or just their memory. That gap is your product.

🎯 Find Your Sharp Edge
"Task management for students" is too broad to win. You need a specific angle that makes students say "this was made for me."
Some sharp positioning examples:

For engineering students juggling lab reports, assignments, and exams across 6 subjects
For college students who procrastinate — built-in focus mode + Pomodoro
For group project survivors — shared task boards for study teams
For exam season — a deadline countdown with priority stacking

Pick one. You can expand later. Trying to serve everyone kills the product.

🏗️ Build the Smallest Useful Thing First
Your MVP should solve one core pain brilliantly, not ten pains poorly.
Realistic MVP scope (4–6 weeks to build):

Add a task with subject, deadline, and priority
Simple home screen showing "what's due today / this week"
One reminder notification
Mark done

That's it. No AI. No analytics. No social features. Ship that, put it in 50 students' hands, and watch what they actually do with it.

🛠️ Tech Stack Recommendation
Since you're non-technical (or early stage), here's the honest path:
StageToolWhyValidate ideaGlide / AdaloLive in days, no codeBuild real MVPFlutterFlowCross-platform, exportable codeScaleFlutter + FirebaseReal engineering, same codebase
Don't hire a developer before validating. A no-code prototype gets you 80% of the learning at 5% of the cost.

📈 The Metrics That Actually Matter Early
Forget downloads. Track:

Day 7 retention — do they come back after a week?
Tasks created per user — are they actually using it?
Session frequency during exam week — does stress drive engagement?

If students use it the week before exams and never after, you have a seasonal tool, not a habit. That changes your whole strategy.

💰 Monetization (Think About It Now, Build It Later)
Three honest models for a student app:

Freemium — Free for basic, ₹99–199/month for power features (best for India)
Institutional B2B — Sell to colleges, not students. One deal = 500 users. Much easier to monetize.
Sponsorships — EdTech brands, coaching institutes, stationery companies pay to reach students.

The B2B institutional angle is massively underplayed. One partnership with a college's student affairs office gets you distribution overnight.

⚠️ The Honest Founder Warning
Student apps are notoriously hard to monetize — students are price-sensitive, churn is high (they graduate), and the market is crowded with free alternatives like Notion and Todoist.
Your moat has to be habit + delight, not just features. The app needs to feel like it was built by a student for students — not by a startup trying to sell to them.
The founders who win this space either:

Build in public with students (make them co-creators), or
Pivot the B2C app into a B2B product sold to institutions


🚀 Your Week-by-Week Plan
Week 1   →  Talk to 20 students. Document pain points.
Week 2   →  Define your sharp angle. Sketch 3 screens on paper.
Week 3   →  Build no-code prototype on Glide/Adalo
Week 4   →  Put it in 50 students' hands. Watch. Listen.
Week 5   →  Kill what they ignore. Double down on what they love.
Week 6+  →  Rebuild properly on FlutterFlow with real insights.

The best student app won't be the one with the most features. It'll be the one that earns a daily habit during the most stressful weeks of a student's life. Build for that moment first.

3. Developer persona
Act as a senior software developer. How should I build a task management mobile app for students?

# OUTPUT:
Great role shift — now you're getting the engineering perspective. Here's how I'd architect and build this as a senior dev.

🏗️ Architecture First — Get This Wrong and You'll Rebuild Everything
The biggest mistake junior devs make is jumping to code. Define your architecture before writing a single line.
Recommended Stack:
Frontend:     Flutter (single codebase → Android + iOS)
Backend:      Node.js + Express (or Firebase for faster MVP)
Database:     Firestore (realtime sync) or PostgreSQL (structured data)
Auth:         Firebase Auth (Google Sign-In = frictionless for students)
Notifications: FCM (Firebase Cloud Messaging)
State Mgmt:   Riverpod or BLoC (Flutter)

📐 System Design
Here's how the core system should be structured:
