This is feature-first architecture — each feature owns its data, domain, and UI. It scales without turning into spaghetti.

⚙️ Core API Endpoints
POST   /auth/google          → Exchange token, return JWT
GET    /tasks                → All tasks (filter: ?subjectId, ?status, ?dueDate)
POST   /tasks                → Create task
PUT    /tasks/:id            → Update task
DELETE /tasks/:id            → Delete task
PATCH  /tasks/:id/status     → Toggle done (separate endpoint = clean audit log)
GET    /subjects             → User's subjects
POST   /subjects             → Add subject

🔔 Notification Architecture
This is where 90% of devs get it wrong. Don't poll — use a trigger.
Firestore task document written
        ↓
Cloud Function triggered (onCreate / onUpdate)
        ↓
Check: is reminderAt in the future?
        ↓
Schedule Cloud Scheduler job at reminderAt
        ↓
Cloud Scheduler fires → HTTP trigger → FCM push to device
Why? If you schedule notifications client-side, they die when the app is killed. Server-side scheduling is reliable regardless of device state.

🧪 Testing Strategy
LayerWhat to testToolDomain modelsTask validation, date logicflutter_testRiverpod providersState transitionsriverpod_testAPI endpointsRoute handlers, auth middlewareJest + SupertestFirestore rulesSecurity rules coverageFirebase Emulator SuiteE2ELogin → create task → mark donePatrol (Flutter)
Aim for 80% coverage on domain and API layers. UI tests are expensive — focus them on critical flows only.

⚠️ Senior Dev Red Flags to Avoid

Putting business logic inside widget build() methods — it belongs in providers
Calling Firestore directly from UI — always go through a repository interface
Not setting Firestore security rules — every document must have request.auth.uid == resource.data.userId
Skipping offline support — students use apps in lecture halls with poor signal; implement Hive local cache with a sync queue
Scheduling reminders on-device only — unreliable when app is backgrounded on Android


🚀 Build Order (Senior Dev Sequence)
Sprint 1   →  Auth flow + Firestore schema + security rules
Sprint 2   →  Task CRUD (API + Flutter data layer, no UI yet)
Sprint 3   →  Task UI (list, add, detail screens)
Sprint 4   →  Subjects + filtering
Sprint 5   →  Notifications (Cloud Functions + FCM)
Sprint 6   →  Offline support + sync queue
Sprint 7   →  Polish, performance profiling, Crashlytics
Build data layer before UI — every time. It forces clean interfaces and prevents you from coupling state to widgets.

